Surprisingly, no — at least not a systematic one. Blue Nile's pricing at 1ct for GIA Excellent does not assign a meaningful premium for 55% tables vs 58% tables within the same color and clarity.

**Real 1ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent stones on Blue Nile:**

| Price | Note |
|-------|------|
| [$3,230](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29090690?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | Check specific table — verify it's 54–57% before purchasing |
| [$3,240](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29090694?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | Second option at nearly identical price |
| [$3,370](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112616?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | Third option — check table % in Cut Details |
| [$3,490](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28941971?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | Fourth option |
| [$3,490](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28215109?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | F-VS2 for comparison — slightly better color at same price |

Among these stones at similar prices, one may have table 55% and another table 57.5%. Both are GIA Excellent. But the 55% stone will show more fire. Since the price is nearly identical, always check and choose the lower table within the acceptable range.

This is free performance. You get a better-performing stone for the same price by spending 30 seconds checking table %.

